<?xml version='1.0' encoding='UTF-8'?>
<ecoSpold xmlns="http://www.EcoInvent.org/EcoSpold02" xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" xsi:schemaLocation="http://www.EcoInvent.org/EcoSpold02 ../../schemas/datasets/EcoSpold02.xsd http://www.EcoInvent.org/UsedUserMasterData ../../schemas/datasets/EcoSpold02UserMasterData.xsd">
  <childActivityDataset>
    <activityDescription>
      <activity specialActivityType="0" id="20c018f5-9f02-5b79-9fee-4afc192367d3" activityNameId="252d25f3-cd32-437e-b5d1-b66589646818" parentActivityId="a55c7a1d-6797-5a53-95aa-3e663a82661a" inheritanceDepth="-1" type="1">
        <activityName xml:lang="en">boric acid production, anhydrous, powder</activityName>
        <synonym xml:lang="en">Borofax</synonym>
        <synonym xml:lang="en">Boracic acid</synonym>
        <synonym xml:lang="en">Orthoboric acid</synonym>
        <synonym xml:lang="en">Boron hydroxide</synonym>
        <synonym xml:lang="en">10043-35-3</synonym>
        <includedActivitiesStart xml:lang="en">The activity starts when the raw materials enter the process.</includedActivitiesStart>
        <includedActivitiesEnd xml:lang="en">This activity includes the consumption of raw materials and chemicals used for the production, emissions to air and the energy demand, as well as the infrastructure use. Solid wastes are omitted.</includedActivitiesEnd>
        <generalComment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">This dataset represents the production of 1 kg of solid anhydrous boric acid (industrial grade). Boric acid is a hydrate of boric oxide. Boric acid crystallizes from an aqueous solution as odorless, white, waxy platelets. The most commercialised form is the trihydrate, orthoboric acid, but boric acid also exists in the monohydrate form, refered to as metaboric acid.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="1">This dataset models the production of orthoboric acid from the reaction of sulfuric acid with colemanite (the most common calcium borate mineral), which is a typical production process used in Europe. Due to a lack of production data, the inventory is based on stoechiometric calculations, as well as data from a large chemical plant (Gendorf 2016).</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="2">References:</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="3">Althaus H.-J., Chudacoff M., Hischier R., Jungbluth N., Osses M. and Primas A. (2007) Life Cycle Inventories of Chemicals. Final report ecoinvent data v2.0 No. 8. Swiss Centre for Life Cycle Inventories, Dübendorf, CH.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="4">Schubert, D. M. 2015. Boric Oxide, Boric Acid, and Borates. Ullmann's Encyclopedia of Industrial Chemistry. 1–32.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="5">Gendorf (2016) Umwelterklärung 2015, Werk Gendorf Industriepark, www.gendorf.de.</text>
        </generalComment>
      </activity>
      <classification classificationId="322d69ab-3e6a-483c-94fb-3d4d650fa7ed">
        <classificationSystem xml:lang="en">ISIC rev.4 ecoinvent</classificationSystem>
        <classificationValue xml:lang="en">0891:Mining of chemical and fertilizer minerals</classificationValue>
      </classification>
      <geography geographyId="0723d252-7e2a-11de-9820-0019e336be3a">
        <shortname xml:lang="en">RER</shortname>
        <comment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">The data used has no specific geographical origin as it is based on stoechiometric calculations and estimations. It is assumed to be representative of the production processes in this geography. Some values are based on data from a large chemical factory located in Germany. These are assumed to be valid for this geography.</text>
        </comment>
      </geography>
      <technology technologyLevel="3">
        <comment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">This dataset models the production of boric acid from colemanite minerals (calcium borates) with the aid of sulfuric acid, with process yield of 95%. As by-product, gypsum (CaSO4) is produced.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="1">The production of boric acid can be summarized with the following reaction equation:</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="2">(2CaO.3B2O3.5H2O) + 2 H2SO4 → 3 (B2O3.3H2O) + 2 CaSO4</text>
        </comment>
      </technology>
      <timePeriod startDate="2000-01-01" endDate="2023-12-31" isDataValidForEntirePeriod="true">
        <comment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">Date of published literature. Some values are based on data published by the Gendorf factory that were collected between 2011 and 2015. The time period has been adjusted accordingly. For more details, see the comments of the exchanges.</text>
        </comment>
      </timePeriod>
      <macroEconomicScenario macroEconomicScenarioId="d9f57f0a-a01f-42eb-a57b-8f18d6635801">
        <name xml:lang="en">Business-as-Usual</name>
      </macroEconomicScenario>
    </activityDescription>
    <flowData>
      <intermediateExchange id="c950baf3-0d08-54d4-bc08-f85a2f0e590a" unitId="487df68b-4994-4027-8fdc-a4dc298257b7" variableName="RP" casNumber="10043-35-3" amount="1.0" intermediateExchangeId="49b0e8ea-9fe2-4790-8532-91bdb99e161f" productionVolumeAmount="11500000.0" productionVolumeVariableName="RP_PV">
        <name xml:lang="en">boric acid, anhydrous, powder</name>
        <unitName xml:lang="en">kg</unitName>
        <comment xml:lang="en">Boric acid is a hydrate of boric oxide. Boric acid crystallizes from an aqueous solution as odorless, white, waxy platelets. The most commercialised form is the trihydrate, orthoboric acid, but boric acid also exists in the monohydrate form, refered to as metaboric acid. It is heavily used in the glass industry while other uses – all of them only of minor importance – are e.g. agricultural fertilizers, soaps and detergents.

References:
Althaus H.-J., Chudacoff M., Hischier R., Jungbluth N., Osses M. and Primas A. (2007) Life Cycle Inventories of Chemicals. Final report ecoinvent data v2.0 No. 8. Swiss Centre for Life Cycle Inventories, Dübendorf, CH.
Schubert, D. M. 2015. Boric Oxide, Boric Acid, and Borates. Ullmann's Encyclopedia of Industrial Chemistry. 1–32.
</comment>
